subSubSection.paragraph:
Ventral surface: Prosternum and metasternum finely pubescent. Metepisternum (
Fig. 60
) about as long as wide, moderately narrowed posteriad. Apex of last visible (VII) abdominal sternite in male widely rounded (
Fig. 61
), in female somewhat angulate at apex (
Fig. 62
).

Male genitalia: Median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 63–66
) in lateral view arcuate, C-shaped, more strongly bent ventrad just after basal bulb, with ventral margin slightly convex in apical half and slightly curved ventrad at apex; in dorsal view median lobe slightly curved to the right, somewhat evenly narrowed to apex in distal half. Terminal lamella (
Fig. 65
) short, narrowed to apex. Apical capitulum large, in lateral view (
Fig. 63
) more strongly prominent dorsally than ventrally, slightly oblique, with ventral flange situated more proximally than dorsal flange, in caudal view (
Fig. 66
) moderately wide oval. Internal sac with a post-medial group of small spines on the right side of median lobe and additionally with a small spine located more distally.
